<Layout
	title="About"
	description="About the Silverback Developer"
	pubDate={new Date('2026-03-03')}
>
	<p>
		I've been writing software since 1976. Twenty-four years at Hewlett-Packard, from software
		engineer to senior architect. A master's in computer science from Colorado State in 1984, and
		a PhD in Systems Engineering — also from CSU — defended in 2024. In between: FORTRAN, Lisp,
		C, C++, C#, Python, et al.
	</p>

	<p>
		I currently co-run a SaaS startup built around MAES — the Mechanistic Air Emissions
		Simulator — a 27,500-line Python codebase used in peer-reviewed research on methane
		emissions from oil and gas facilities. It is not a toy codebase. Decisions about how
		to maintain and improve it are business decisions, not just engineering preferences.
	</p>

	<p>
		This blog documents my experience using agentic AI tools — specifically Claude — as part of
		my daily development workflow. Not as a convert, not as a skeptic. As an engineer with
		enough experience to tell the difference between a tool that genuinely changes how you work
		and one that generates impressive-looking output that is actually useless.
	</p>

	<p>
		I'll be specific. I'll show actual prompts and actual output. I'll tell you when it helped
		and when it didn't.
	</p>

	<p>
		For the longer version: <a href="/blog/post-00-about-me">50 Years of Code — Why I'm Finally Letting an AI Help</a>.
	</p>
</Layout>
